values:
With the Olympic games now just days away, I can't help but be extremely bothered by the fact that they are being held in China. Yes, this is the most populous nation in the world, and yes they were cheated out of the 2000 games when they lost selection by two votes - two votes that turned out to have been bought. Even so, there are just too many reasons why China does not deserve the Olympic games. 

While transforming itself into an economic powerhouse, the Chinese government has destroyed the surrounding environment. Sure, this is their choice, and most Chinese are very happy with the influx of money, and newfound individual economic power. But decades from now, when asthma and cancer rates are through the roof, fish and wildlife have been destroyed, the only thing they'll have left is a surplus of over-polluting factories. Only then will they realize that they didn't really have a choice but to live with the most polluted air in the world; the government was going to do that whether the people liked it or not.&nbsp; The Ethiopian world record holder for the marathon has decided to run a shorter distance because of the damage the air will do to his lungs. Athletes from America and other countries are planning to wear breathing masks up to the last moment before their events begin. Until then they're trying to find ways to do their pre-event training indoors. 

Their One Child Policy has encouraged sex selective abortion, and scewed (sp?) their sex ratio. Government policy penalizes public officials who do not curb policy growth. So while not officially endorsed by the government, this policy encourages lower level officials to force sterilization and abortion. 

The People's Republic of China continues to control its citizens by denying freedom of speech and freedom of the press. International reporters have recently discovered that their internet access will be limited during the Olympic events, despite past promises that they could cover the games in whatever way they saw fit. Now, a google search for "Tipet" will be restricted. Finding unrestricted access to the internet is extremely difficult for ordinary citizens, and the country continues to do everything it can to restrict access to information from the outside world.&nbsp;

The other day I saw a report on the legacy of Chairman Mao. All over China there are still giant statues and portraits of Mao, along with art, jewelry and coins in his image. A new biography was just released, written in Chinese, but is censored in China because it tells the truth about what he did (ie, not the state sanctioned history). Thirty years after his death they are still using propaganda to promote his greatness. This is the man responsible for the Great Leap Forward, which led to millions of Chinese starving to death, probably the largest famine in world history. After that there was the Cultural Revolution. Afraid of being forced out, he empowered the Red Guards creating social and economic chaos. Schools were closed, people were wrongly imprisoned and hundreds of thousands were killed. And Mao is still celebrated as a great man!

Perhaps most relevant to the outcome of the games are the ways that China treats its athletes. The government is determined to come out with the most medals, and has essentially created athlete factories, taking children from a very young age and training them from a very young age. NPR has done spent a lot of time covering this story. Many young athletes are pushed too hard, and face crippling injuries. Others (MOST) simply come to the end of their training at a level that is not high enough to compete on the world stage. In either case, these athletes are thrown aside by the government, offered no compensation and left without an education, since they have opted to join these athletic academies, leaving no time for schooling. Even former medal winners have been pushed to the point of injury, left with nothing, and forced to sell their medals for cash. This sort of Olympian factory goes against the spirit of the games.&nbsp;

How does this even bolster your international image? Who won the most medals in the 2006 Olympics? I have no idea. I'm sure most people wouldn't know. (just checked. it was Germany.) I don't think that people of the world feel any sort of profound respect for Germany. They don't really care. Winning the most gold medals won't get you any more respect when you're oppressing your own people, and enabling genocide in Darfur. Oh, and did I mention Tibet? The point is: Olympic victory is temporary!&nbsp;

Athletes were forced to sign agreements stating that they will not make political remarks against China or the games, in order to prevent incidents like the Black Power Salute at the 1968 Summer Olympics. The idea of awarding the Games to China was that the world spotlight would foster positive change, the way that the 88 games advanced Korea's transition to democracy. But history has shown that regimes have used the Olympics to increase nationalism and become stronger, as the Nazis did. Once the games end, the attention is gone. That's why it's so important that the media and the athletes do everything they can to highlight the atrocities being committed by the Chinese government, to force reform while they can, and let the Chinese people know that they deserve better.

If this doesn't happen, then the only thing to come out of the Olympics is THE STORY of the first Chinese Olympics. It will get a lot of attention, bring in a lot of viewers and a lot of dollars (or euros or yen or whatever). Beijing will be left with some really cool, interesting architecture, but not much else.

This year, I'm giving up buying books for lent. I realize that I have a problem. Hopefully this will&nbsp;prevent my library from growing to further monstrous proportions, if only temporarily. AWP weekend can be considered my Fat Tuesday, because I bought more books than I should have, even with Catie's "don't" glares keeping me in check most of the time. I've been meaning to read something by Jennifer Egan, so I bought her novel "Look at Me." And finally I bought "Another Bullshit Night In Suck City" which sounds like a pretty good memoir. Also I found a book of poetry based on female super hero characters. Nice. I think I'll give that one to Ian. On top of that I got a few copies of "One Story" magazine, which is really cool. 

The fact that I've held out for this long is surprising. When we were in Boston I spent a day "shopping" with Catie, Angie, and her friend Yee. I managed to hang in there for .. oh, two stores. But after that I was sick of looking at clothes. So I spent an hour in Barnes and Noble, and another hour in Borders. It was torture! When Easter comes there will be a feast - a feast of books. I'd really like to get something by Stewart O'Nann. Sal wrote about him in his blog and most of his books sound really good. I'd also like to get something by Dennis Johnson. There are a lot of modern authors who I still haven't explored, and need to. There's a book called "History of a Bad Year" that has a really cool structure. It's about an old professor who hires an assistant for dictation and help with his book. Every page of the book is divided into thirds. The top third is the content of the political book being written. The middle third is the professor's thoughts. And the bottom third is the thoughts of the girl. I'm not sure how you actually go about reading that though. It's like reading a really long jump page.&nbsp; 

My obsessive reading habits actually helped me to write a great cover letter to be a researcher at Panel Intelligence. I cast myself an information junkie, always on the lookout for my next fix, and I wanted Panel Intelligence to be my new dealer.&nbsp;Well, it wasn't QUITE that radical, but it was really fun to write&nbsp;a creative cover letter after writing a dozen boring letters.&nbsp; 

I want to channel my obsessive reading more towards reading books, and writing short stories. If only there were a way to escape internet news. The primaries will be over soon, which is a relief, I can stop agonizing over whether or not Obama will blow it to Hillary. But then the baseball season starts and I MUST have a fantasy team, and I MUST obsess over it. I'm determined to win. On the bright side, I don't have any drug or alcohol problems. On the downside, I am lame.&nbsp; 

At some point I should post a list of all the books I read last year. And no, I didn't make it to fifty.

In two weeks I must travel sixteen hundred miles in three days by myself and my car still has not heat. My only prayer for a safe return may be a heat wave in middle of December, which is not entirely unlikely considering how sporatic the weather has been lately.&nbsp;

The cold itself doesn't bother me. If I had to I would wear three layers and wrap myself under blankets. But if I can't defrost my windows then I can't see. Driving further south might solve some problems. Or maybe I'd be better off doing a non stop bolt across the country. Wait for an opening in the weather then make a twelve hour dash. LIke so many problems in my life right now, this may be an instance of "wait and see."

If I had money right now I could pay someone to take a look at it. The anti freeze levels are fine. And I checked the fuses, suspecting that the fuze powering the blower had burned out. But that doesn't seem to be the case. Perhaps the blower needs to be replaced. Or perhaps it is something even more complicated than that. Either way, my checking account is usually hovering near the nothing mark, so it's a moot point. Health insurance and rent suck up virtually all of my money right now. The rest is spent on whatever gas and groceries I can afford. I eagerly await a $700 check from Gary Fincke to arrive in my mailbox. Did I mention that I won the first place prize in ESSAY magazine a few weeks ago? Well, I did, for my literary journalism piece about the laundry fire at the Hampton. It was around the same time as the Meredith break up, so there wasn't much celebrating. Plus, what then looked like a windfall of magic cash, now seems like something I need just to scrape by and make it back home.&nbsp;

It's horrible to think that money will solve all the problems in your life, but a few hundred bucks would make my life far easier right now. Once I'm home I won't have to worry about rent anymore. And hopefully my Highmark Blue Shield coverage will kick in ASAP at the Hampton so I can ditch these outrageous COBRA payments. THEN maybe I can start working my way out of debt. 

Yesterday I drove to Greeley for my treatment. While I was there I finished reading The Grace that Keeps this World. I was extremely impressed. The crowning moment of Tom Bailey's lifes work. Impressive. Then I slept for a long time because there was nothing else to do other than watch The View. An older man was sitting next to me,&nbsp;and when he came back from the bathroom, rolling his IV pole behind him,&nbsp;he stopped in front of me and said "Looks like we're getting the same stuff." I was pretty out of it, but stil managed a little surprise; I'd never met anyone who recieved the same treatment as I did. "How long have you been getting it?" he asked. I said, "Since I was eleven or twelve, I think. Before that I just got it in shots. But then I got older and the Gulf War sucked up&nbsp;a lot of that supply, so I started getting it this way instead."&nbsp;"Oh," he said. "I've been getting this every twenty eight days since July."&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So.... I still haven't met anyone with my condition. He only needs it because as he got older his immune system became weaker. My immune system has always been this bad. Oh well.

At least my treatment is taken care of before I have to leave. There's also been some interest in the apartment from a few different people. I was about to start freaking about that, but after a few days on Craigs list we've had about five inquiries, including two separate people from Africa. But, frankly, those two just have too many questions and special circumstances and it seems like it would just be too complicated to transfer the apartment to either of them. But thanks anywyas Craigslist, for getting&nbsp;the word out in Africa.&nbsp;

Today I'm going to do some packing and try to get a grasp on just how much stuff I'll have to squeeze into my car. Is it possible to get some sort of small heater for my car. Would that work? I've also considered some sort of battery powered hair dryer.

There's been some big news lately. Britney Spears lost her House... or something. Oh wait, no, that's not it. Now I remember. Some of the top villains of American politics are now out of power. Or, at least out of office. (I'm sure they'll weasel their way back into "power" in some way, still wielding their influence in America). The Democrats control the House, and will control the Senate once the Virginia recount is over with.&nbsp;Not a single Democratic incumbent lost their bid for re-election.

Two Republican Presidential hopefuls have faced huge setbacks now that they've been rejected&nbsp; by the constituents of their state. Rick Santorum was anti-gay, believed in making America a Theocracy, and believes that a woman's place is in the home, and that many women choose to work because it's "a novelty." George Allen, also most likely out of the Senate. He was thought of as one of the most likely to become the GOP's 2008 nominee, having been described as "a George W. Bush clone." Now Mr. Allen has been revealed as a racist. Not to mention the fact that, being like George W. Bush, is&nbsp;no longer considered a positive trait. (about time) And now Rumsfeld, the man who has micromanaged nearly every mistake made in the Iraq war, has resigned. It's surprising that the resignation was announced a day after the election. If it had been done a week earlier it could have been seen as a sign that Bush was truly willing to change course and the Republicans probably would have held onto a handful of seats.&nbsp;

A few weeks ago I realized why Bush and Rove were so insistent to keep Rumsfeld where he was. If Rumsfeld had resigned, then there would have had to be hearings to confirm his replacement. Such a hearing would have amounted to a hearing that would have revealed every&nbsp; mistake made in the Iraq War, and how and why each decision was made. George W. Bush truly believed that the Republicans could retain the House and Senate, he said so himself at a press conference yesterday. (side not, at the Press Conference Bush made no effort to hide just how annoyed he was by the election results. It was a sight to see) Now that the Democrats are in power, it was invetiable that there would have been hearings on Rumsfeld's performance.&nbsp;

It's a shame that this political situation was able to go on for so long. Rove is a genius, albeit an evil one. Once the GOP was in power, he knew the best way to stay in power was to have the White House, House of Representatives and Senate be in agreement on every issue. There was never any questioning of decisions being made. Anyone brave enough to put forth an opposing view was quickly villainized. Governing was little more than one continuous campaign, with every action taken with the purpose of gaining more power.&nbsp;

Now, the Christian Revolution is over. The reign of the Neocons is over. Just months ago it seemed as though the Democrats may not win another election in our lifetimes. Now there is hope.

A couple weeks ago I drove to Denver for a Barack Obama book reading. They could only guarentee that the first 350 people would be able to personally meet Senator Obama and have their books signed, so I showed up an hour early to be safe. Unfortunatlely, there were already people lined up outside at four a.m. even though the book store didn't open until seven and the Obama wasn't arriving until noon. There were probably about 100 people in front of me when they reached the 350 person limit. The crowds stuck around anyways, just to catch a glance of Obama. There was such excitement in the air. In the end, I had a chance to see Obama walk through the crowd, every bit as charismatic as he seems on TV. I then stood in the corner of the Small Business Books section listening to Senator Obama speak for five minutes about the Audacity of Hope. "it's easy to be cynical and to believe in the worst. The hard thing is to hope for&nbsp;a world better than the one we have." (rough quote) &nbsp;It was worth the hour drive.

Admittedly, I'm a news junkie. Everyday I read The Washington Post and New York Times online and sometimes look over USA Today as well. And now I have a subscription to the Denver Post, too. This is way too much news, and I'm trying to keep it under control. But after months of political obsessing I finally feel a payoff. Maybe now there will be withdrawal from Iraq, raise in the minimum wage, affordable health care, and fair trade instead of free trade. But I still worry. Lately I've started listening to AirAmerica, the Al Franken led liberal talk radio channel. When you're folding laundry for hours on end you start to get sick of every song on the radio and just want to hear human voices for a while. Some of the show's are thoughtful and informative. But others... are just crazy. Believe me, the far left is just as frightening as the far right.&nbsp;

Hopefully the Democrats will remember that many of their seats were won because they ran moderates, not ultra liberals. So how about a toast to moderation. Let's hope that all elected officials work together, put aside the endless campaign and work on solving problems.&nbsp;

Oh yeah, Bayh/Obama 08.

Cheers!

Are there discrimination laws about hiring smokers? In the event that I ever own a business I think it would be my policy not to hire smokers.&nbsp;

This is not a personal grudge against smokers (well, it is somewhat now that I think about it). But I don't care if people smoke. Some of my friends smoke. And that's their business. I like to smoke when I'm drunk. My prioblem is working with people who smoke.&nbsp;

The problem with people who smoke cigarettes is: they're addicted to cigarettes. Smokers need to take cigarette breaks while they're working, usually several breaks per shift. If they don't get their breaks then they become irritable, ie, bad employees. This has been a problem with at least one individual at every job I've ever worked.&nbsp;Nonsmokers can get by (usually) with only one break per shift.&nbsp;

This past weekend was Homecoming weekend at CSU, so the hotel was sold out. That means there was a lot of laundry to clean and a lot of guests to help. When I came in on Saturday afternoon, I found that a lot of the things that should have been done in the monring shift were not done (by the smoker). It was nothing huge, nothing hard to do, just things that took time. The housekeeping manager told me that he took at least three cigarette breaks. Now you consider that not only do smokers take time to go outside and actually smoke, but when they return from their break, they usually have to take a few minutes to catch their breath and recover from their break.&nbsp;

This is just bad business. Why hire somebody who is wasting your time like this? If you want into go into more about smokers costing people money, just think about how much they cost by increasing health care premiums for employers/employees. This is a touchy subject for me because of how much I have to pay for health care.&nbsp;

Think about it, and tell me if I'm wrong.

Currently there's a group of people staying at the hotel for the Dickson Ninja Retreat. This sounds like the most amazing event ever. I wasn't sure if these were people who were training to become ninjas, or if these were ninjas hoping to escape from the everyday hustle and buetle of everyday ninja life. Most of my night was spent looking over my shoulder, paranoid that these ninjas were hiding behind shrubs, inside the laundry chute, etc, etc. They're a stealthy bunch, and you can never be too cautious when it comes to their brood. But then again, if aa ninja wishes to kill, he will kill. End of story.&nbsp;

Perhaps I should brush up on my "Real Ultimate Power Book" (everything you can ever hope to learn about ninjas), but I seem to have left it in Pennsylvania.

I'm doomed.

Right now I'm watching Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure. Earlier this morning, before work, Bill and Ted's Bogus Journey was on TV. Looks like my guardian angel is working extra hard today.

My car has been acting weird lately.... I think. It started a few weeks ago when I took my&nbsp; car for an Emissions test. Colorado requires everyone to pass Emissions tests, but doesn't require that your car be "inspected." Oh Coloardo, you're not like Pennsylvania. So anyways, all of my emissions numbers were good, but I still passed the test because my car was "smoking up." I didn't really understand, but the mechanic told me I could go to t he garage next door and they would change my oil and put in some sort of smoke reducing magic liquid. So I did that then waited a few weeks for my car to be healed. But in the meantime my car started feeling a lillle strange. My brakes squeeled and the steering has at times felt erratic. Plus the check engine light came on. Ugh.&nbsp;

I tend to be paranoid about my car. Sometimes I think I'll hear a noise, but it's hard to tell because a lot of the music I listen to uses a lot of squeals, grinds, and menacing hums.&nbsp;

Another problem was that I couldn't pass the emissions test with the check engine light on, because they'll fail you for that, too. But I decided that I would have it re-tested anyways, b/c maybe they would find out what was happening with my car. Of course I would never be able to figure this out by myself. I know how to check my fluids and stuff, but other than that, if I suspect something is wrong I usually end up opening the hood, looking inside and thinking "It looks like everything is working.. "

On the drive to Jiffy Lube my Check Engine light magically turned off, which was amazing. So I was able to pass the test. But with a catch. The mechanic (a different one this time) comes out and says "Well you got lucky. You passed." And he says it in this really arrogant attitude like I was trying to get away with something, or like I knew exactly what was wrong with my car but didn't want to do anything about it. I was so confused. Did he find something wrong with my car? Why would he say I got lucky? I still don't even understand what makes a car "smoke up." Furthermore, I did exactly what the other mechanic told me to do, and I have no idea what else I could have done had the smoke reducing elixir been ineffective. Ugh.

My dad has showed me "car stuff" dozens of times, but it never sinks in. That piece of my brain is apparently retarded. If this "man" area of my brain truly is dead, perhaps that would explain why I don't like watching football or lifting weights. But really, it's unfair that just because I'm a man I'm expected to know car things. Just like how I'm expected to know how to fix any computer problem just because I wear glasses and like Star Wars. This is a prime example of how I am a just another victim in this male dominated society. Stupid men. I hate them.&nbsp;

The check engine light has gotten into a cycle of turning on and off, on and off. Who knows what that means. Things haven't been going incredibly great at my new job. There have been many times when I've absolutely hated it and blamed it for ruining my life. And so I've considered the possibilty that maybe&nbsp; the Check Engine light isn't really telling me to look at the engine. Perhaps it's telling me to examine MYSELF. Eh? Isn't this where we truly need a check engine light: on the human heart.&nbsp;Shouldn't we be focusing less on&nbsp;the little pieces inside a car, and more on the big emotions we're feeling inside?&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; ....&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; You may want to reference the section above about me not being a real man.&nbsp; : /&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

The other night Alex alerted me to Steve Irwin's death. I told Meredith and she said "I also heard that Kel from Keenan and Kel died." Now, for the record, Kel is the one who was NOT Fat Albert and was NOT on SNL. So anyways, I told Alex about it, but a few seconds later Meredith said that she had heard about this on MySpace, ie, the most reliable source of news in the world, so I told Al to forget it.&nbsp;

We were able to prove that Kel is still alive by looking at IMDB and seeing that he has some new projects coming out (such as, Like Mike 2. Clearly, that movie needed a sequel).&nbsp;

Alex and I then noticed the IMDB message board on Kel's page. The first post is "PROOF HE IS NOT DEAD... CHECK THIS OUT", followed by "HE IS NOT DEAD"&nbsp;,&nbsp; "RIP KEL MITCHELL"&nbsp; "I've got proof he's not dead"&nbsp;&nbsp; and "Kel, please show up."&nbsp;&nbsp; Amazing! There is some pretty pathetic/hilarious stuff on the IMDB message boards. This was easily the funniest thing I'd seen or heard all week.

The alleged "proof" offered by one person was "If he died then wouldn't it be on the news?"&nbsp;&nbsp; No, you idiot. No, it would not be on the news. This is Kel Mitchell, not a real celebrity. Another post provided a link that was supposed to give proof that Kel was alive, but the link led you to a petition to get the Pepper Ann cartoon released on DVD.&nbsp;

Here are some other things that people said:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "WOW my friend at school told me he died, and I was crushed."
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "I hear a rumor like once a year that he has died!"
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; "I heard this rumour about 7 years ago wen I were at school. apparently they were both in a car crash and kel died and keenan was on a life support machine... weird how the rumour are still alive."

Many of the people seemed very upset that someone would dare spread these rumors over MySpace while Kel is alive and well being a husband and father. Wow.


In other fake news, the new Nip/Tuck season premiers tonight. It promises to be the best season ever, for one reason: Mario Lopez. Saved by the Bell's Mario Lopez guest stars on the show as a gay plastic surgeon that Christian may have a fling with. Ha. I found a screen shot on MySpace that shows Dr. Troy and A.C. Slater together in a public shower. WHAAAT? Craziest show ever. But then again, i did see this news on MySpace so I suppose I shouldn't be believing any of this.
